Hi and Happy New Year ☆ I wanted to thank everyone for donating and sharing my gofundme//posts so far. It means the world. I have another surgery on Wednesday and we will continue to work on my mouth area for the next few months. This has been traumatic and of course during an already stressful time. I know the holidays drained everyone and it's slow season all around but the link to donate is in my bio and I'd appreciate if we could throw it around a little more. I hope everyone had a really enjoyable evening yesterday. I didn't get to dress up fancy and go all out.. but I did manage to see some fireworks through the fog. It was beautiful.
Thank you Dani from @punkwebs for grabbing me from surgery this last week and gifting me this cozy beautiful top. Please check her shop out it's incredible. 
I don't think I will show my full face anytime soon.. but I will manage to make my recovery as fashionable as possible. 
☆
Love to my friends and the people I don't know personally that are giving me the means to recover and keep up with the facial reconstruction. 
♡

Trigger Warning- I put some slides in order of the healing and surgeries thus far! Hopefully the black and white photos don't get deleted and if you don't like injuries don't click it 🙄 I love my surgeons and am incredibly happy with the care I've received and excited to share it ♡ My face has healed up SO well. Last week we started injecting my mouth with steroids and things and they want me to get that every 6 weeks since the scar tissue is super bad. We can't add permanent volume to the damaged side until it's gone 🥲 I'm seeing facial plastics again in May but need to go to an oral surgeon and dentist about my teeth. I'm still struggling to eat solid food but in 8 weeks that should be taken care of ! I'll have to get some new back teeth, caps and braces... but damn. I am VERY happy I didn't lose the front ones 😬 my dental work will be insane and my insurance will not cover it so please check out the gofundme link in my bio ♡ Anyway I would not be getting through this without all the support while recovering 🥺♡ thank you♡

This photo hit me like a ton of bricks. Just a group of kids at a show. Thinking about Liz today. It's been 10 years. I'm the last one standing in this picture and it made me throw up. Punk can be violent, there's suicides and murders and overdoses and all of my friends in this memory.. met those things. No matter what the hell life throws at me I'm sticking it out for them. They were strong people and serious punk fckn warriors. I believe that you can create a good future for yourself.. I never thought so but I'm hopeful. It's just a lot to know you can't share that future with your crew. Much love to the SLC mates today. She was a gem and probably the sweetest one of us all.

I haven't taken many 'selfies' since my skull fractures. I just feel like I look different. I mean .. I got my face Frankensteined back together with metal 🤯 I can very much tell where it's not me. Lately I've been feeling more like myself though. Mentally and physically ♡ I'm not hiding a smashed up face anymore, my plastic surgeon is making sure I'm happy with my mouth, & I can get oral surgery in the next couple months to fix the stuff we couldn't before. All positive things ✨️ I can't feel my front teeth yet but within the last few days I've had meals I was DREAMING about while recovering. I have to be gentle but omg does food impact you mentally. It's funny what you miss ♡ I'm learning patience.
My GFM link is still up in my bio to pay off//pay for the dental and to keep getting injections until I can get permanent plastic surgery ♡♡♡ 
Thank you to everyone ♡

Holmesburg Prison is evil as it is beautiful. The controversial prison (that is still used for inmate overflow) was built in the 1800s and has gone down in history as the place where men were "baked" to death as a form of punishment, s*xually assaulted and were given meals (they were starved) to be used for dermatological, pharmaceutical, and biochemical weapons research involving testing on human subjects. The inhumane medical experiments influenced the government to set up ethical standards that we now follow today. Albert Kligman famously recounted entering the Holmesburg Prison for the first time as:
"'All I saw before me were acres of skin. It was like a farmer seeing a fertile field for the first time.'"
Basically it was a medieval dungeon that was still doing awful things until the late 1980s 🙃

He joined my grandma in their final resting place this last weekend and I can't seem to find the right words. How do you talk about people who lived such extraordinary lives and were so very admirable ? After 66 years together they will go on next to eachother still. I've never seen two people that in love.
.

He constantly told me I looked like I fell off a tortilla truck with messy hair and I would NEED to catch the fish for dinner or we weren't eating ( they were all jokes but honestly ... I did have to catch fish ) Love ya Papa. Love you Grandma. Rest easy.
.
*and yes that's little me***

It's #worldmsday ! I love my support group and don't know how I'd get through all this without them ♡ having people to talk to who also manage this disease has literally saved me. Today is a day for us and our care teams ♡ to bring awareness, to lend a hand to someone newly diagnosed, to honor the people who passed this last year and to those of us that are taking it one day at a time ♡ MS has taken a lot from me but it gifted me optimism & I don't take the good days for granted. Going on three years (two since we figured out what the symptoms were from) and my recent MRIs came back with no new brain lesions ♡♡♡♡ everyone I know with #MS is such a strong individual. It blows my mind how we can push through all the hospital appointments on top of not having control over our bodies & brain. The medical cost alone and navigating life with a disability is ... it's so much. My love goes out to everyone battling it. The posts keep getting me choked up. Such positivity and support 😭 Here's to another year of us being total fighters ☆

Having this illness means constantly advocating for myself. This is what I'm learning to manage. Even when life is hectic and I feel physically and mentally depleted.. I still have to keep on top of it.. (as in piles of paperwork) For the rest of my life. Good days and... bad. Currently compiling my list of ED visits and hospital stays and who the attending doctors were//treatment ...since 2020 🤪 found some of those bills I forgot about and once again we filed a grievance because my insurance really just doesn't care if I'm going back to the hospital on the 5th ❤️‍🩹 MS is the little monster on my back but I'm learning to carry it. Grateful for the support from my little community.
